  "languages": {
    "en": {
      "text": "The approach of a future event describes the steadily decreasing interval between the present moment and a forthcoming occurrence. As a temporal property, it captures the essence of time drawing closer — the sense that something anticipated is moving from the distant future into imminent reality. This concept is central to how humans perceive and organize their experience of time, distinguishing between events that remain far off and those that are nearly upon us. In everyday language, people speak of \"the approach of winter,\" \"the coming of dawn,\" or \"the approaching deadline,\" all evoking this same notion of temporal narrowing. The concept belongs to a broader family of temporal qualities that includes timing itself, as well as related properties such as earliness, lateness, and punctuality.",
